01:07.720 --> 01:13.800
As software is deeply involved in all our lives, it's important that it empowers us

01:13.800 --> 01:16.160
rather than restricting us.

01:16.160 --> 01:19.520
And we think that free software is crucial for that.

01:19.520 --> 01:23.600
We've been around for more than 20 years, have been campaigning legally and politically

01:23.600 --> 01:26.000
for free software and open source software.

01:26.000 --> 01:30.040
And we're relying on a strong community across Europe.

01:30.040 --> 01:37.520
So to give you a brief outline of my talk, first I'll talk about why does it make a difference,

01:37.520 --> 01:43.480
why does free software really matter, not only for your daily coding work, for your

01:43.480 --> 01:49.400
daily computer work, but also in building a sustainable and digital Europe that's ready

01:49.400 --> 01:51.920
for innovation and freedom.

01:51.920 --> 01:56.200
And a lot of the things that I'm going to tell you in the first part of my talk will

01:56.200 --> 02:00.240
be familiar to you, but I think it's good to put it together so you can use it as arguments

02:00.240 --> 02:05.280
when talking to your local administrations or to your politicians.

02:05.280 --> 02:13.240
So in the second step, I will show the PMPC campaign to you, which has been, yeah, we

02:13.240 --> 02:15.640
have been running it since 2017.

02:15.640 --> 02:20.280
And during last year's, it has gained a lot of momentum and has become a key part of the

02:20.280 --> 02:23.800
push for free software all over Europe.

02:23.800 --> 02:27.920
The last part, which will be the main focus of my talk, is how you can get involved in

02:27.920 --> 02:30.280
promoting free software.

02:30.280 --> 02:33.560
So let me start with a brief explanation of free software.

02:33.560 --> 02:35.280
I think definitions are important.

02:35.280 --> 02:40.360
And also if you talk to politicians and to administrations, always make sure that you

02:40.360 --> 02:43.760
have the same understanding of what you're talking about.

02:43.760 --> 02:48.360
So I think you're all familiar with the U.S. military chain of commands.

02:48.360 --> 02:56.240
There are the unified combat commanders, the secretary of defense, and on top of the hierarchy,

02:56.240 --> 02:58.120
of course, we have the president.

02:58.120 --> 03:04.000
He's the one who has to decide to press the red button or hopefully not to press it.

03:04.000 --> 03:09.680
But what about the guy, what about the girl or woman, the person who installed the red

03:09.680 --> 03:11.000
button?

03:11.000 --> 03:13.520
Can we be sure that it does what it should?

03:13.520 --> 03:16.400
And can we be sure that it works only when it's pushed?

03:16.400 --> 03:19.120
This is of some importance for us too.

03:19.120 --> 03:23.640
And this is one problem that free software can solve, but there are a lot of others.

03:23.640 --> 03:26.240
So what is free software?

03:26.240 --> 03:32.120
Free software grants everybody, everyone, for fundamental rights or for freedoms, the

03:32.120 --> 03:37.440
freedoms to use, to study, to share, and to improve the software.

03:37.440 --> 03:39.000
What does this mean?

03:39.000 --> 03:40.720
You can use anybody.

03:40.720 --> 03:42.400
Anyone can use the software for any purpose.

03:42.400 --> 03:43.600
There are no restrictions.

03:43.600 --> 03:46.240
You can do with it whatever you want.

03:46.240 --> 03:47.240
You can look into the code.

03:47.240 --> 03:51.480
You can study it and you can analyze it and also others can analyze it and find out what

03:51.480 --> 03:54.120
is going on behind the curtains.

03:54.120 --> 03:55.680
You can share the code.

03:55.680 --> 03:58.360
The software can be shared without limitations.

03:58.360 --> 04:01.000
And of course, you can also earn money with it.

04:01.000 --> 04:05.560
You don't have to sell it, but you can make money with it depending on your business model.

04:05.560 --> 04:09.760
Many people do, many developers do that and many companies.

04:09.760 --> 04:12.800
And you can, of course, improve the software.

04:12.800 --> 04:17.440
Also to make it better, you can, of course, also make it worse, but hopefully make it

04:17.440 --> 04:23.680
better and give it back to the community so others can work on it too and use it too.

04:23.680 --> 04:29.800
So why does free software matter to public bodies?

04:29.800 --> 04:33.440
Why should public bodies support free software?

04:33.440 --> 04:41.520
There are two fundamental mechanisms that are important for public bodies.

04:41.520 --> 04:44.280
One of them is digital sovereignty.

04:44.280 --> 04:49.520
So in order to establish trustworthy systems, public bodies must ensure that they have full

04:49.520 --> 04:56.040
control over the software and the computer systems at the core of all state digital infrastructure.

04:56.040 --> 04:57.920
This is very important.

04:57.920 --> 05:06.400
And the other basic maxim is tax money must be spent in the most efficient way possible.

05:06.400 --> 05:08.840
So public bodies are financed through taxes.

05:08.840 --> 05:13.120
They must make sure that they spend the funds in the most efficient way possible.

05:13.120 --> 05:19.040
And both maxims are undermined by the use of proprietary software.

05:19.040 --> 05:22.160
So let's have a look at some of the problems with proprietary software.

05:22.160 --> 05:26.400
First, there's no interoperability.

05:26.400 --> 05:32.840
So you all know situations where somebody sends you a file made with a proprietary software

05:32.840 --> 05:38.840
and you have to buy the software in order to open it or work with it or even buy a new

05:38.840 --> 05:42.160
computer and install a proprietary operating system.

05:42.160 --> 05:46.000
This of course also applies to administrations.

05:46.000 --> 05:48.640
And it leads to vendor lock-in.

05:48.640 --> 05:53.680
So administrations have to stick to their software solution if they use proprietary

05:53.680 --> 05:57.320
software not to lose compatibility, to be able to work together.

05:57.320 --> 05:59.280
And this is a big problem.

05:59.280 --> 06:03.240
It leads to unpredictable costs.

06:03.240 --> 06:06.320
You never know what next year's license cost will be.

06:06.320 --> 06:08.480
You have to pay for the upgrade in any way.

06:08.480 --> 06:09.480
You have to do it.

06:09.480 --> 06:16.160
You lock in and you have no chance to escape that if you're using proprietary software.

06:16.160 --> 06:20.680
And these investments that you are making, they are lost.

06:20.680 --> 06:23.000
They go to the vendor for the license.

06:23.000 --> 06:28.760
And you don't know if the software is made better with your money or even not.

06:28.760 --> 06:35.600
Maybe some features implemented you as an administration can't benefit from.

06:35.600 --> 06:38.840
So you don't have much control over new features.

06:38.840 --> 06:41.040
It's a vendor's decision.

06:41.040 --> 06:42.040
There's lack of transparency.

06:42.040 --> 06:50.240
We know from research and also from experience, for example, during the COVID pandemic, that

06:50.240 --> 06:56.400
there's low acceptance among citizens for proprietary digital services.

06:56.400 --> 07:02.240
So for example, the COVID tracking apps, we know that people respond better to them and

07:02.240 --> 07:08.360
attempt to using them more if they are free software open source.

07:08.360 --> 07:13.480
And if they know that their privacy, their fundamental rights and data protection also

07:13.480 --> 07:15.280
are guaranteed.

07:15.280 --> 07:18.880
And this leads also to the last point, security concerns.

07:18.880 --> 07:19.880
Trust is good.

07:19.880 --> 07:22.840
Trusting proprietary software can be dangerous.

07:22.840 --> 07:27.180
You never can show that there aren't any bugs, aren't any security holes or backdoors.

07:27.180 --> 07:30.560
So the solution for all of this is, of course, free software.

07:30.560 --> 07:34.200
With free software, you have interoperability through open standards.

07:34.200 --> 07:39.020
Free software and open standards are crucial for that and crucial for working across borders

07:39.020 --> 07:44.840
or across systems from other vendors.

07:44.840 --> 07:47.080
Free licenses give you independence.

07:47.080 --> 07:48.080
There is no vendor lock-in.

07:48.080 --> 07:52.340
Administrations are free to move to different solutions.

07:52.340 --> 07:58.180
And you can also, in the long run, save costs by using free software through collaboration.

07:58.180 --> 08:00.840
So free software, as we all know, is based on collaboration.

08:00.840 --> 08:03.640
Public bodies will benefit from this.

08:03.640 --> 08:08.480
If they adapt existing software or decide on joint procurement, for example, they can

08:08.480 --> 08:11.800
share risks and save money in the long run.

08:11.800 --> 08:14.960
And more and more examples for this kind of cooperation exist.

08:14.960 --> 08:19.520
I will come back with some examples a bit later.

08:19.520 --> 08:24.240
If you, as an administration, as a local government, are using free software, you can empower

08:24.240 --> 08:25.840
your local partners.

08:25.840 --> 08:30.920
If you opt for free software, you empower local IT companies instead of paying license

08:30.920 --> 08:34.320
fees to international or transnational corporations.

08:34.320 --> 08:39.040
And your local economy will benefit from this tax money.

08:39.040 --> 08:42.680
It will often be small and medium enterprises, SMEs.

08:42.680 --> 08:49.440
This makes a huge difference for your region, for your city, for your country and the citizens.

08:49.440 --> 08:51.320
Free software is transparent by default.

08:51.320 --> 08:56.360
This validates privacy, full data protection, and fundamental rights.

08:56.360 --> 09:00.560
And as I said, this is key to a higher acceptance by the citizens.

09:00.560 --> 09:04.360
And finally, free software code, as we all know, can be audited.

09:04.360 --> 09:05.600
We can look into it.

09:05.600 --> 09:08.360
Of course, it's not automatically free of bugs.

09:08.360 --> 09:14.560
And security problems, but publicly verifiable code is a prerequisite for finding these bugs

09:14.560 --> 09:20.480
and security problems and not leaving the security of critical infrastructures to proprietary

09:20.480 --> 09:22.600
companies.

09:22.600 --> 09:30.320
So let's have a look at the government's effect on IT companies, which effect can a

09:30.320 --> 09:34.000
free software policy have on the IT industry?

09:34.000 --> 09:43.920
Governments are among the largest IT purchasers, accounting for up to 27% of software companies'

09:43.920 --> 09:44.920
revenues.

09:44.920 --> 09:50.640
If we convince governments to spend money on free software rather than licenses, this

09:50.640 --> 09:55.160
can really make a huge difference for the whole IT economics.

09:55.160 --> 10:02.000
And we have a huge influence on economy, especially SMEs again, and your local economy.

10:02.000 --> 10:07.720
Given these numbers, what if public bodies decide on free software when procuring?

10:07.720 --> 10:14.920
What if free software becomes default locally, regionally, but also in your country or throughout

10:14.920 --> 10:15.920
Europe?

10:15.920 --> 10:21.320
First, as we said, tax savings, similar applications don't have to be programmed from scratch

10:21.320 --> 10:23.320
every time.

10:23.320 --> 10:29.320
So tax savings in the long run, if you can use software or parts from other projects,

10:29.320 --> 10:33.600
improve and adapt it, share and give back so others can do the same.

10:33.600 --> 10:38.800
Second, there's collaboration, major projects can share expertise and costs.

10:38.800 --> 10:43.600
Third, you serve the public by using free software, so applications paid by the public

10:43.600 --> 10:46.120
should be available to everyone.

10:46.120 --> 10:50.200
And lastly, fostering innovation.

10:50.200 --> 10:56.600
If you withdraw transparent processes, others don't have to reinvent the wheel and you can

10:56.600 --> 11:02.280
use brands and money to invent something new to come up with new solutions and new ideas.

11:02.280 --> 11:10.360
Instead of funding the same corporations for the same products again and again, SMEs can

11:10.360 --> 11:12.320
benefit from this.

11:12.320 --> 11:15.760
So let's have a look at some examples.

11:15.760 --> 11:21.440
France, for example, implemented a free software friendly politic for steps in that direction

11:21.440 --> 11:23.160
back in 2012.

11:23.160 --> 11:24.160
And what happened?

11:24.160 --> 11:31.640
In France, we saw up to 5.4 year increase in companies that use free software.

11:31.640 --> 11:38.840
We saw up to 18% yearly increase in the number of IT related startups, up to 14% yearly increase

11:38.840 --> 11:42.000
in the number of individuals employed in IT related jobs.

11:42.000 --> 11:44.160
This is very impressive, I think.

11:44.160 --> 11:52.760
And interesting side note, also up to 16% less software related patents.

11:52.760 --> 12:04.240
So yeah, if you as a government opt for free software, you can really make a difference

12:04.240 --> 12:06.840
also for your economy.

12:06.840 --> 12:12.200
And some more examples, looking at the city of Barcelona, which is a very famous example

12:12.200 --> 12:18.960
for the implementation of free software, they decided some years ago to spend 70% of their

12:18.960 --> 12:21.000
IT budget on free software projects.

12:21.000 --> 12:27.120
It's not everything, it's not 100%, but it's better and a lot better than nothing.

12:27.120 --> 12:31.160
And they decided also to collaborate with other cities.

12:31.160 --> 12:32.160
What happened?

12:32.160 --> 12:41.080
From 3,000 companies involved in the local IT business, 60% were SMEs, many from the

12:41.080 --> 12:42.600
region, of course.

12:42.600 --> 12:48.840
So the reasons for using free software in your administration, in your region, are not

12:48.840 --> 12:53.400
only technical, it's not only sovereignty, tax efficiency, but there are also good economic

12:53.400 --> 12:54.400
reasons to do so.

12:54.400 --> 12:57.560
And this is very interesting for politicians, of course.

12:57.560 --> 13:01.440
So Barcelona took a very important decision.

13:01.440 --> 13:05.640
They decided not to switch all systems at the same time, but went step by step.

13:05.640 --> 13:10.800
We know from other examples, from Munich, for example, with the Linux project that they

13:10.800 --> 13:20.240
decided to do a really fast change to free software to Linux in their administration,

13:20.240 --> 13:26.600
and it wasn't well accepted by many people working there, and it led to complexities.

13:26.600 --> 13:29.480
So we think the better idea is to do it step by step.

13:29.480 --> 13:33.240
So whenever new software is procured, go for free software.

13:33.240 --> 13:36.320
Whenever a license runs out, go for free software.

13:36.320 --> 13:42.240
And one other example, this time from Germany, there's a collaboration of nine municipalities

13:42.240 --> 13:43.600
from southern Germany.

13:43.600 --> 13:51.800
They call themselves Ready, and they decided to develop solutions together.

13:51.800 --> 13:58.640
So the starting point was during the COVID crisis when they started using a JITC implementation

13:58.640 --> 14:01.880
called it Palim-Palim.

14:01.880 --> 14:08.960
And they found it to be very useful for doing library lectures online, and other cities

14:08.960 --> 14:14.840
found it to be also very fitting their needs, and they decided to collaborate and exchange

14:14.840 --> 14:20.400
knowledge and work together on this and also on many other projects.

14:20.400 --> 14:24.520
So to cut along, shall we start?

14:24.520 --> 14:29.360
Why should administration support free software, regionality, autonomy, efficiency?

14:29.360 --> 14:33.840
When SMEs can become strong partners, free software helps to develop and maintain tailored

14:33.840 --> 14:37.760
software that suits your needs, not just the vendor's business model.

14:37.760 --> 14:41.520
And with transparent processes, others don't have to reinvent the wheel.

14:41.520 --> 14:45.360
Native products can share expertise and costs.

14:45.360 --> 14:52.480
Yes, of course, I gave you some examples, but there are many, many hundreds, thousands

14:52.480 --> 14:57.320
of cities throughout Europe who have not yet adapted free software.

14:57.320 --> 15:02.440
This is why we as the FSFE, Free Software Foundation Europe, decided back in 2017 to

15:02.440 --> 15:05.680
