I will use that better than for the video.

20:12.400 --> 20:14.200
Or maybe in the end.

20:14.200 --> 20:17.600
And the video I think is also out in about ten languages.

20:17.600 --> 20:24.760
So you can use it for your regional and country.

20:24.760 --> 20:30.520
Also if you want to contribute to the campaign, where can you start?

20:30.520 --> 20:35.520
You can of course focus on the national or international level.

20:35.520 --> 20:40.600
But you have to be aware that this is a long way to go and a lot of work.

20:40.600 --> 20:45.000
So if you have a long breath and staying power, then go for it.

20:45.000 --> 20:46.880
But there are other levels to start with.

20:46.880 --> 20:53.560
You can for example at your university or you can talk to your library, your local job

20:53.560 --> 21:00.880
agency or the school administration where during the COVID, again the COVID pandemic,

21:00.880 --> 21:04.720
everybody started to use Zoom or Google teams or something like that.

21:04.720 --> 21:08.440
Microsoft teams.

21:08.440 --> 21:13.800
And now maybe the next invoices for the next licenses are already on the table of the head

21:13.800 --> 21:18.880
of the department or they see that they need something more sustainable.

21:18.880 --> 21:24.360
Or they are even not really aware that there is something else like the Plubartan or Jitsi.

21:24.360 --> 21:27.660
So go to them and tell them.

21:27.660 --> 21:31.640
So acting on a local or regional level will be easier and success there will be a lower

21:31.640 --> 21:34.040
hanging fruit for you.

21:34.040 --> 21:35.040
Who can you reach out to?

21:35.040 --> 21:37.280
Who can you approach?

21:37.280 --> 21:42.160
Of course decision makers, so your city council, regional parliament, it makes sense.

21:42.160 --> 21:48.160
Go to talk to people from different institutions, also from different parties.

21:48.160 --> 21:54.800
And maybe also to an admin from your IT apartment, you might even find allies there who share

21:54.800 --> 21:58.200
the same view and help you.

21:58.200 --> 22:03.040
Don't be afraid of talking to people who might not share your views or to a party you're

22:03.040 --> 22:05.360
not leaning towards.

22:05.360 --> 22:11.040
Reach out, meet, talk, be friendly, even if they don't support you at first, you don't

22:11.040 --> 22:12.040
have anything to lose.

22:12.040 --> 22:13.040
You can just win.

22:13.040 --> 22:16.360
In the long run, you will maybe even change their minds.

22:16.360 --> 22:23.560
So really try to talk to everybody, not just to the persons you know that they are probably

22:23.560 --> 22:26.520
already convinced of public money, public code.

22:26.520 --> 22:27.520
What can you do?

22:27.520 --> 22:28.760
So how?

22:28.760 --> 22:32.840
Use the definitions, the examples and arguments I was talking about before.

22:32.840 --> 22:35.880
We are pretty sure for more information on that.

22:35.880 --> 22:36.880
Adapt your examples.

22:36.880 --> 22:37.880
This is very important.

22:37.880 --> 22:43.800
So if you're from Spain and you want to talk to a Spanish government, then maybe use the

22:43.800 --> 22:51.000
numbers from Barcelona or from Asturias better than from France or vice versa.

22:51.000 --> 22:52.480
Choose your arguments wisely.

22:52.480 --> 22:59.800
So if you're talking to somebody from a left-leaning party, maybe it's not so good to emphasize

22:59.800 --> 23:04.080
the economic arguments but more sustainability and empowering the people.

23:04.080 --> 23:08.960
If you're talking to someone from a liberal party or leaning towards the liberal side,

23:08.960 --> 23:10.520
economic is of course good.

23:10.520 --> 23:16.720
And conservative parties might be more interested in national sovereignty and how it is threatened

23:16.720 --> 23:17.720
by them to lock in.

23:17.720 --> 23:21.640
And free software is of course the gold standard in security.

23:21.640 --> 23:29.320
And most important thing, even if you don't have success at the moment, remain friendly.

23:29.320 --> 23:38.760
So an example, what you can achieve from Germany, the biggest conservative party in Germany,

23:38.760 --> 23:45.280
back in 2019, they decided to back our demand for public money, public code.

23:45.280 --> 23:46.280
This is also possible.

23:46.280 --> 23:51.640
And of course, don't hesitate to welcome such decisions.

23:51.640 --> 23:55.800
It's important to convince everybody of free software because it's making us as a community

23:55.800 --> 24:01.600
independent from who is having the government at the moment.

24:01.600 --> 24:10.240
And finally, when?

24:10.240 --> 24:14.520
Timing matters for your activities, keep your eyes open for relevant developments in your

24:14.520 --> 24:15.520
region.

24:15.520 --> 24:18.760
Are there any news about plans for a new IT strategy?

24:18.760 --> 24:20.880
Is there a new head of the IT department?

24:20.880 --> 24:23.920
Are there problems with school video conferencing tools?

24:23.920 --> 24:25.440
Don't miss these opportunities.

24:25.440 --> 24:29.680
Step in and talk about the best alternatives.

24:29.680 --> 24:32.560
But also don't wait for things to happen.

24:32.560 --> 24:34.800
Don't wait for such occasions.

24:34.800 --> 24:36.240
Rather be proactive.

24:36.240 --> 24:38.680
Writing or talking is never wrong.

24:38.680 --> 24:42.840
Keep in mind, if you do that, answers will take time.

24:42.840 --> 24:44.880
Be patient.

24:44.880 --> 24:49.520
Maybe write a friendly reminder after some weeks when you didn't get an answer.

24:49.520 --> 24:53.680
And after an appointment, be sure to always follow up and keep the communication going.

24:53.680 --> 24:54.680
Be always friendly.

24:54.680 --> 25:00.360
Very, very important, as I said before, because angry tweets or toots will close doors rather

25:00.360 --> 25:02.680
than opening it.

25:02.680 --> 25:05.360
So finally, one more example.

25:05.360 --> 25:06.920
Again from Spain.

25:06.920 --> 25:13.640
So very Spain and Germany focused here.

25:13.640 --> 25:15.360
This time from Orviedo.

25:15.360 --> 25:18.840
It's a community in the region of Asturias.

25:18.840 --> 25:20.680
Maybe somebody in the picture is also in the room.

25:20.680 --> 25:21.680
I don't know.

25:21.680 --> 25:29.520
There was a little hack lab, the Pika-Pika hack lab, and they decided back in 2015 to

25:29.520 --> 25:34.400
start demanding public money, public code from their local authorities.

25:34.400 --> 25:40.360
And they didn't have success at first, but then they got into contact with our campaign

25:40.360 --> 25:47.760
and they used our materials and they really had a long breath reaching out to communities

25:47.760 --> 25:54.600
and used these arguments to all parties, towards all parties, and convinced many people.

25:54.600 --> 25:59.360
They wrote emails and they managed to get face-to-face meetings, which is very important

25:59.360 --> 26:01.360
if you reach out to politicians.

26:01.360 --> 26:02.720
And they had a little social hack.

26:02.720 --> 26:07.880
So once you're inside the parliament, you have to get inside somehow and somebody has

26:07.880 --> 26:08.880
to let you in.

26:08.880 --> 26:12.480
But once you're inside, you can just knock doors and doors will open.

26:12.480 --> 26:16.860
So find somebody who lets you in the parliament.

26:16.860 --> 26:22.560
So what they managed to do is the parliament of Asturias, of the bigger region in Spain,

26:22.560 --> 26:26.220
stating the parliament of Asturias commits itself to the international public money,

26:26.220 --> 26:27.700
public code campaign.

26:27.700 --> 26:30.520
This is not legally binding, but it's a first step.

26:30.520 --> 26:35.200
And what is also really, really important, people now there understand free software,

26:35.200 --> 26:38.600
the politicians.

26:38.600 --> 26:41.840
What does success mean for your approaches?

26:41.840 --> 26:46.600
So if you can get somebody to sign the letter, if you can get a government to sign the letter

26:46.600 --> 26:49.720
or parliament, this of course really, really good.

26:49.720 --> 26:54.800
But don't be frustrated if a library board decides against free software or if the city

26:54.800 --> 27:01.700
council PMPC statement has loopholes or things move slowly in administrations.

27:01.700 --> 27:03.880
Sometimes you really need to have a long breath.

27:03.880 --> 27:06.520
But you've talked and you've convinced someone.

27:06.520 --> 27:12.240
And we have time, we have a long breath, and we will finally succeed.

27:12.240 --> 27:16.080
So that was the main thing of my talk.

27:16.080 --> 27:22.000
Really, if you want, you can come up to our booth at a set in Building K, level one.

27:22.000 --> 27:23.920
Just take some material there.

27:23.920 --> 27:29.100
And also, if you want to support the FSFE's work, you can do that with a donation.

27:29.100 --> 27:34.120
We would be very grateful for that because we're a charity and we depend on donations.

27:34.120 --> 27:39.240
And you have the chance also to get your copy of this really lovely children's book, which

27:39.240 --> 27:43.440
explains the idea behind free software to children.

27:43.440 --> 27:46.360
So thank you for listening.

27:46.360 --> 27:50.400
And yes, I'm open for questions.

27:50.400 --> 28:01.240
We have time for one question and I have seen one hand.

28:01.240 --> 28:03.880
Excellent.

28:03.880 --> 28:06.560
Maybe two questions if people speak quickly.

28:06.560 --> 28:14.600
Yeah, I think that it did not come out from your talk if there's public money, public

28:14.600 --> 28:15.600
codes.

28:15.600 --> 28:19.960
This means they save a lot of money if they now choose open source software.

28:19.960 --> 28:22.640
How much developer do they hire?

28:22.640 --> 28:28.720
Do they do audits or is it now just all the open source software projects have much more

28:28.720 --> 28:30.720
users which are not developer?

28:30.720 --> 28:41.160
The open source project has now much more users and these users have ideas and maybe

28:41.160 --> 28:43.080
find bugs.

28:43.080 --> 28:50.400
But the amount of developers seems not to increase or who does the audits for the software

28:50.400 --> 28:54.720
that the public domains are using now.

28:54.720 --> 29:02.400
This is also in your plan from the free software foundation just to save them money for what?

29:02.400 --> 29:12.960
The question is to say this company's public company is public money and use public codes.

29:12.960 --> 29:15.160
So they save a lot of money.

29:15.160 --> 29:18.680
Did they hire any open source developer?

29:18.680 --> 29:19.680
Yeah.

29:19.680 --> 29:20.680
So the idea is...

29:20.680 --> 29:21.680
Who say audits?

29:21.680 --> 29:23.040
Who has the work?

29:23.040 --> 29:27.640
The idea is of course not to take away the money from the companies.

29:27.640 --> 29:35.680
The idea is of course that the money is used in a better way and we all know that software

29:35.680 --> 29:42.520
developers have to be paid somehow but it should be rather through maintenance fees

29:42.520 --> 29:49.240
and through development of new features or audits than through license fees.

29:49.240 --> 29:53.400
This is what we also try with this campaign to tell them.

29:53.400 --> 29:55.920
Okay, so only one question.

29:55.920 --> 29:57.680
It is only one question, yeah.

29:57.680 --> 29:59.360
Building K for more.

29:59.360 --> 30:00.360
Wonderful people.

30:00.360 --> 30:01.360
Yeah.

30:01.360 --> 30:02.360
Thank you very much for having us.

30:02.360 --> 30:20.160
Thank you very much.
